<exercisegroup cols="2">
<title>Interpreting augmented matrices</title>

<introduction><p>
	For each matrix,
	write out a system of equations whose <term><xref ref="definition-systems-augmatrix" text="title" /></term> is the one given.
	Then determine the solution(s) to the system.
</p></introduction>

<exercise>
	<statement><p><m>\displaystyle
		\begin{amatrix}{rr|r}
			1 \amp 2 \amp 5 \\
			0 \amp 1 \amp 2
		\end{amatrix}
	</m></p></statement>
	<solution><p>
		Using variables <m>x</m> and <m>y</m>,
		the corresponding system is
		<me>
			\begin{sysofeqns}{rcrcr}
				x \amp + \amp 2 y \amp = \amp 5 \\
					\amp   \amp   y \amp = \amp 2
			\end{sysofeqns}
		</me>.
		From the second equation,
		we immediately have <m>y = 2</m>,
		and we can substitute that value into the first equation to obtain
		<md alignment="gather">
			<mrow> x + 2 y = 5 </mrow>
			<mrow> x + 2 \cdot 2 = 5 </mrow>
			<mrow> x + 4 = 5 </mrow>
			<mrow> x = 5 - 4 </mrow>
			<mrow> x = 1 </mrow>
		</md>.
		So the solution to the system is <m>x = 1, y = 2</m>.
	</p></solution>
</exercise>

<exercise>
	<statement><p><m>\displaystyle
		\begin{amatrix}{rr|r}
			1 \amp -2 \amp 0 \\
			0 \amp  1 \amp 3 \\
			0 \amp  0 \amp 0
		\end{amatrix}
	</m></p></statement>
	<solution><p>
		Using variables <m>x</m> and <m>y</m>,
		the corresponding system is
		<me>
			\begin{sysofeqns}{rcrcr}
					x \amp - \amp 2 y \amp = \amp 0 \\
					\amp   \amp   y \amp = \amp 3 \\
				0 x \amp + \amp 0 y \amp = \amp 0
			\end{sysofeqns}
		</me>.
		Notice that the third equation essentially says <m>0 = 0</m>,
		which is true but contains no useful information.
		From the second equation,
		we immediately have <m>y = 3</m>,
		and we can substitute that value into the first equation to obtain
		<md alignment="gather">
			<mrow> x - 2 y = 0 </mrow>
			<mrow> x - 2 \cdot 3 = 0 </mrow>
			<mrow> x - 6 = 0 </mrow>
			<mrow> x = 6 </mrow>
		</md>.
		So the solution to the system is <m>x = 6, y = 3</m>.
	</p></solution>
</exercise>

<exercise xml:id="exercise-systems-interpret-augmented-3vars">
	<statement><p><m>\displaystyle
		\begin{amatrix}{rrr|r}
			1 \amp -3 \amp -2 \amp  5 \\
			0 \amp  1 \amp  3 \amp -3 \\
			0 \amp  0 \amp  1 \amp  2
		\end{amatrix}
	</m></p></statement>
	<solution><p>
		Using variables <m>x,y,z</m> the corresponding system is
		<me>
			\begin{sysofeqns}{rcrcrcr}
					x \amp - \amp 3 y \amp - \amp 2 z \amp = \amp  5 \\
					\amp   \amp   y \amp + \amp 3 z \amp = \amp -3 \\
					\amp   \amp     \amp   \amp   z \amp = \amp  2
			\end{sysofeqns}
		</me>.
		From the third equation,
		we immediately have <m>z = 2</m>,
		and we can substitute that value into the second equation to obtain
		<md alignment="gather">
			<mrow> y + 3 z = -3 </mrow>
			<mrow> y + 3 \cdot 2 = -3 </mrow>
			<mrow> y + 6 = -3 </mrow>
			<mrow> y = -9 </mrow>
		</md>.
		Knowing values for both <m>y</m> and <m>z</m>,
		we can substitute them into the first equation to obtain
		<md alignment="gather">
			<mrow> x - 3 y - 2 z = 5 </mrow>
			<mrow> x - 3 \cdot (-9) - 2 \cdot 2 = 5 </mrow>
			<mrow> x + 23 = 5 </mrow>
			<mrow> x = - 18 </mrow>
		</md>.
		So the solution to the system is <m>x = -18, y = -9, z = 2</m>.
	</p></solution>
</exercise>

<exercise>
	<statement><p><m>\displaystyle
		\begin{amatrix}{rrr|r}
			1 \amp -3 \amp -2 \amp  5 \\
			0 \amp  1 \amp  3 \amp -3 \\
			0 \amp  0 \amp  1 \amp  2 \\
			0 \amp  0 \amp  0 \amp  4
		\end{amatrix}
	</m></p></statement>
	<solution><p>
		Using variables <m>x,y,z</m> the corresponding system is
		<me>
			\begin{sysofeqns}{rcrcrcr}
					x \amp - \amp 3 y \amp - \amp 2 z \amp = \amp  5 \\
					\amp   \amp   y \amp + \amp 3 z \amp = \amp -3 \\
					\amp   \amp     \amp   \amp   z \amp = \amp  2 \\
				0 x \amp + \amp 0 y \amp + \amp 0 z \amp = \amp  4
			\end{sysofeqns}
		</me>.
		At first glance this seems very similar to the system from <xref ref="exercise-systems-interpret-augmented-3vars" text="type-local" />.
		However, here we have a fourth equation that essentially says <m>0 = 4</m>,
		which is <alert>false</alert>,
		and there is no combination of values for <m>x,y,z</m> that will make it true.
		So while the values <m>x = -18, y = -9, z = 2</m> will simultaneously satisfy the first three equations in the system,
		there is <alert>no</alert> combination of variable values that will simultaneously satisfy all <em>four</em> equations,
		and therefore the system is inconsistent.
	</p></solution>
</exercise>

</exercisegroup>
